Hawaii 🌸 was more than I could have imagined, and I will forever be grateful for @bigislandrollerderby, my host @kaypasa840 and everyone who went out of their way to help me make the most beautiful memories, including: @6_bamz Bamz, Greg @chop_smitty and Jen, @punapunstar, Bandit @banditangel18 and Smash @smash_derby_skills 

I met local adult and junior skaters, two really good groups I enjoyed teaching to.

After our time together, I was brought around the Big Island to do and see so, so much. 

I was taken to different beaches (black volcano sand! White coral sand!) and got to snorkel in bright indigo waters. I peacefully floated observing giant cauliflower coral formations and so, so many fish 🐠, all vibrantly colourful (parrot fish! Look it up!)

I swam in fresh water that flowed through the forests following ancient lava tubes through the mountains. 

I was offered the gift of a lifetime (thank you Greg and Jen!) to be taken up where only scientists, engineers and their personal guests are allowed, to the Canada France Hawaii Telescope to observe the stars from one of the darkest places on earth. 

I was driven up in a sturdy, reinforced Ford truck (!) to the top of Mauna Kea, a dormant volcano, the sacred domain of snow goddess Poliʻahu, more than 13 700 feet high (that’s about half Mount Everest!) way above the clouds, where the oxygen is thin. After the sun set, I stood still on the telescope’s building platform, in complete darkness (couldn’t see my own hands!) waiting for my eyes to adapt, and slowly they all appeared. The shiniest stars first, then the faint and the dim, and finally the Milky Way itself so close it felt like I was in a dome. 🌌 For once, I had not a word to explain, just pure and absolute awe and the deepest closeness to everything and everyone.

So much happened! Instagram isn’t the platform.

I have a book to write, to collect the cherished memories of all these trips and hopefully INSPIRE MANY TO REACH OUT TO LEAGUES! Go meet other people who love what you love! 

Most leagues have policies in place to welcome outside guests, wether you want to drop in practices or need a place to stay for a few days. 

Can’t encourage you more.

📣 Roller Derby Training: Jammer Flow! 🌊 ✨

When jammers engage packs with bold motions, they oblige the formation to answer back in a similar way, and a flow-effect may begin as the blockers attempt to track and control the space and speed of the jammer. 

Generally, a jammer that learns to resist the urge of simply engaging themselves as soon as they notice an opening will develop their pack navigation skills, and will secure themselves safer passages over time. They will learn how to become more manipulative in their motions. 

The key is to work the formation by timing the direction switches at the peak of the blocker’s commitment to the roll, creating pendulum-like swings: short and long diagonal direction switches timed just right, always chasing the tail of the wave of motion. 

Here’s a clip and a demonstration of the skill taken by an attendee of the weekend camp I coached in beautiful Yukon, hosted by the @yukonrollerderby

This is part of a 45 minutes training block with many more weight transfer techniques. I couldn’t put it all here, but this is a good start. 

Hope this helps you all with your jammer training! 💪
